<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ops-automation-workflow">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>growth-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Identify, prioritize, and build business automations that replace repetitive manual tasks. Time-audit process, ROI matrix, workflow patterns, and tool selection.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>workflow</tag>
      <tag>marketing-ops</tag>
      <tag>roi</tag>
      <tag>integration</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Automation and Workflow</title>

    <summary>A methodology for identifying, prioritizing, and building business automations that replace repetitive manual tasks. Covers a time-audit process, ROI prioritization matrix, tool selection, and workflow design patterns for lead capture, onboarding, content distribution, and reporting. The core rule: manually define and run a process at least once before automating it — automating an undefined process creates a faster path to wrong outcomes.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Repetitive tasks (lead capture, email sequences, social posting, data sync) compound into hours of weekly overhead and introduce human errors. Automation converts these to zero-marginal-cost operations, freeing capacity for strategy and relationships. The ROI threshold is >5x return in year one: (time saved × occurrences/month) ÷ (build time + monthly maintenance).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Identified repetitive tasks consuming 30+ minutes per day or 1+ hour per week</item>
        <item>Error-prone manual process where mistakes have downstream cost (payment, data sync)</item>
        <item>Customer lifecycle event (signup, purchase, milestone) that always triggers the same steps</item>
        <item>Weekly or daily reporting pulled manually from multiple tools</item>
        <item>Content distribution that follows the same steps after each new piece</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Process not yet defined — automate only what has been run manually and understood</item>
        <item>Decision-heavy workflow requiring judgment — automation handles triggers, not strategy</item>
        <item>Rare task (less than monthly) where build time exceeds annual time savings</item>
        <item>Tool integrations are unstable or in active development — automation will break</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="time-audit-process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track all activities for one week before selecting automation targets. Do not automate based on memory — track actual time spent.</statement>
        <rationale>Perceived time cost is unreliable. People underestimate daily tasks (done automatically) and overestimate rare tasks (memorable but infrequent). One week of tracking reveals the actual cost distribution.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Repetitive: same email, same data entry, same lookup — automate</item>
        <item>Sequential: multi-step processes triggered by an event — automate</item>
        <item>Scheduled: daily or weekly recurring tasks — automate</item>
        <item>Decision-heavy: strategy, creative judgment — do not automate</item>
        <item>Relationship: sales calls, personal support — partially automate (prep, follow-up)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="automation-roi-formula">
      <rule>
        <statement>Only build automations with a projected ROI greater than 5x in the first year. Below this threshold, maintenance overhead typically exceeds the time saved.</statement>
        <rationale>Automations require ongoing maintenance (tool updates, API changes, logic fixes). Low-ROI automations become net-negative over a 12-month period when maintenance is factored in.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>ROI = (time saved per occurrence x occurrences per month) / (build time + monthly maintenance time). Target: >5x annual return.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="prioritization-matrix">
      <list>
        <item>High priority: daily task, 30+ minutes → automate first</item>
        <item>High priority: error-prone process with costly mistakes (payment, data sync)</item>
        <item>Medium priority: weekly task, 1+ hour → automate second</item>
        <item>Medium priority: impacts customer experience directly</item>
        <item>Low priority: rare task (less than monthly)</item>
        <item>Skip: nice-to-have convenience with minimal time cost</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="lead-capture-automation">
      <rule>
        <statement>The lead capture automation must fire within 5 minutes of form submission. Leads contacted after 30 minutes convert at 21x lower rates than leads contacted within 5 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>Intent decays rapidly. A lead who filled a form is in a buying moment. Automated immediate response preserves that moment regardless of timezone or time of day.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Trigger: form submission</item>
        <item>1. Add to CRM or email list with tags from form data</item>
        <item>2. Send welcome email with next step</item>
        <item>3. Notify founder/sales via Slack</item>
        <item>4. Create follow-up task in CRM (Day 2)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="customer-onboarding-automation">
      <list>
        <item>Trigger: payment confirmed or signup completed</item>
        <item>Day 0: Welcome email + access credentials</item>
        <item>Day 1: Getting started guide</item>
        <item>Day 3: Check-in email</item>
        <item>Day 7: Feature highlight</item>
        <item>Day 14: Feedback request (NPS or CSAT)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="content-distribution-automation">
      <list>
        <item>Trigger: new blog post published (RSS feed change)</item>
        <item>1. Create Twitter/X post with excerpt and link</item>
        <item>2. Create LinkedIn post with excerpt and link</item>
        <item>3. Add to next newsletter issue (queue)</item>
        <item>4. Update sitemap</item>
        <item>5. Log in tracking sheet</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="weekly-reporting-automation">
      <list>
        <item>Trigger: Monday 9am (cron schedule)</item>
        <item>1. Pull metrics from analytics, revenue, and product tools via API</item>
        <item>2. Format into weekly report template</item>
        <item>3. Send to email or Slack</item>
        <item>4. Archive to Google Sheet row</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="robustness-requirements">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every automation must have: error notification, logging, and a manual fallback path. Silent failures are more damaging than no automation.</statement>
        <rationale>An automation that fails silently (no notification, no log) produces incorrect business state without any signal. A failed lead capture automation means lost leads with no visibility. The manual fallback ensures the process continues even when the automation breaks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Error notification: Slack or email alert when automation fails</item>
        <item>Logging: record each execution with timestamp and status</item>
        <item>Manual fallback: documented steps to run the process without the automation</item>
        <item>Testing: run with sample data before going live</item>
        <item>Staging period: run automation in parallel with manual process for 1 week</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tool-selection">
      <list>
        <item>Zapier: best for general integrations, no-code, wide app coverage, $Free-599/mo</item>
        <item>Make (formerly Integromat): complex multi-step workflows, visual builder, $Free-299/mo</item>
        <item>n8n: self-hosted, developer-friendly, full control, $Free-50/mo</item>
        <item>IFTTT: simple single-trigger automations, $Free-5/mo</item>
        <item>Pipedream: developer-friendly, serverless, JavaScript/Python, $Free-199/mo</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>For self-hosted environments or complex pipelines requiring custom code, use n8n over Zapier. For quick no-code integrations between popular SaaS tools, use Zapier.</statement>
        <rationale>n8n provides full code execution (Python, JavaScript) and self-hosting, eliminating per-task pricing and data privacy concerns. Zapier provides faster setup with a larger pre-built connector library.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Automating a process before running it manually at least twice and documenting the exact steps.</description>
        <reason>An undefined process cannot be correctly automated. Automating ambiguity at machine speed produces large-scale incorrect outcomes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Building complex branching logic into a single automation workflow.</description>
        <reason>Complex automations are fragile and hard to debug. Split complex logic into simpler, chained automations. Each automation should do one thing clearly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Setting up an automation and not reviewing it for 3+ months.</description>
        <reason>APIs change, SaaS tools update, data formats shift. An unreviewed automation silently breaks months after deployment. Review all active automations monthly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/automation-audit.md" purpose="Weekly time audit: daily tasks, event-based tasks, total manual hours"/>
      <template path="templates/automation-design-doc.md" purpose="Single automation spec: trigger, workflow steps, error handling, testing"/>
      <template path="templates/automation-inventory.md" purpose="Active automation registry: name, trigger, actions, status"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
